Natural solutions are part of the answer, but are by themselves insufficient. Affordable technological systems for removing excess emissions from the atmosphere are lacking and none is built for an all-electric future.

Using only electricity, our technology platform can remove carbon dioxide both directly from the air and from emission sources. This means we can flexibly help our partners achieve their climate targets in the most affordable way.

We are a technology-based company developing a solution to implement in road pavements that promotes safer, smarter and more sustainable cities.

The World Health Organization points to road accidents as the 8th leading cause of death in the world and defines excessive speed as the main cause of road accidents. The existing solutions to reduce vehicle speeds are all depending on the drivers’ behaviour. Pavnext presents the first solution to implement in the infrastructure of the city that reduces the vehicles’ speed without any driver action, without inducing discomfort to the vehicle’ occupants, without generating noise and without requiring for any device in the vehicle.

Since our devices are implemented in the road pavement, these have a privileged position to monitor traffic data, both in terms of counting vehicles, measuring their speed and weight. Also, it monitors the energy produced and stored in real-time. Combining both data, our solution is able to optimize energy consumptions in real-time and according to the real needs, as well as to provide traffic reports to local and governmental authorities.

The EU commission has employed different institutions and consulting companies to develop a tool that makes it possible to compare and define the CO2 emissions generated by new trucks. This tool is called VECTO.

The fact that trucks are used in different applications means that they generate different CO2 emissions. Hence, the VECTO task force created average mission profiles to cluster different applications into regional or long-haul fleet application clusters – also called mission profiles.

The characteristic fundamentals of such mission profiles are: Average loading (empty and full), the share of regional and highway usage, topography, and others. For the purpose of defining CO2 emission at the beginning of a truck’s lifecycle, this methodology is useful and will help to reduce CO2 emissions

We improve energy and operating efficiency of electric-powered industrial machines by offering an end-to-end hardware & software solution that enables manufacturers and end-users to remotely monitor performance of their machines in real time.

Elmodis was founded by an experienced team of engineers that had worked for more than 20 years for European industrial customers in the areas of machine monitoring and diagnostics, prescriptive, maintenance and energy efficiency. The Elmodis novel way of machine monitoring is based on measuring current and voltage from electric motors powering those machines and combining this data with process parameters to provide a complete picture. The Elmodis solution takes measurements of the electric energy that flows through the whole machine, and calculates hundreds of important parameters in real­time to give clients detailed and useful information about the performance and state of their machines. Using data provided by Elmodis, machine manufacturers can reduce warranty repair costs and ultimately build better products. Industrial end­ users can optimize their energy consumption and prevent failures from incorrect usage.

Dove Renewables owns two hydro schemes. The Norbury weir scheme is a wholly-owned 100 kW single turbine hydro scheme on the River Dove in the Peak District. It was built in 2016 and was partly funded by an £800,000 bond promoted by Triodos Bank. The scheme was commissioned in December 2016 and has been performing to target since.

Dove Renewables also owns a 56% stake in the Sowton weir scheme on the River Teign on Dartmoor which began operating in 2013.

The two schemes generate an average of 820 MWh of clean electricity each year – enough to power the equivalent of approximately 200 homes.
